{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489441"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"662"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/662"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.13,0.08,0.15,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54677"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/662"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40204"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1762"},{"type":"tags","id":"2935"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4565"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54677"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-year history of increased pigmentation and blistering of both hands. She has noticed that her skin blisters even after minor trauma. She also reports that her urine is tea-coloured. She has a medical history of hepatitis as a child and several blood transfusions. She does not take any regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill which she has been taking for 25 years. She has a 30 pack-year smoking history and reports significant alcohol use. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is excessive terminal hair growth on her cheeks and temples, not following a pattern of male distribution. Her hands show areas of hyperpigmentation and small blisters (Image). There are no lesions on her mucosal membranes. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bullous pemphigoid","Epidermolysis bullosa","Scleroderma","Bullous lupus erythematosus","Porphyria cutanea tarda"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eporphyria cutanea tarda\u003C/strong\u003E (PCT), which is the most common type of porphyria. PCT typically arises in middle to late adult life, consistent with this patient\u0027s age. The patient exhibits several characteristic features of PCT, including blistering of sun-exposed areas (hands) that worsens with minor trauma, hyperpigmentation, hypertrichosis (excessive hair growth) on the face, and dark, tea-coloured urine due to the presence of uroporphyrins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPorphyria cutanea tarda is a metabolic disorder characterised by a deficiency in the enzyme uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase (UROD), which is involved in haem biosynthesis. This deficiency leads to an accumulation of uroporphyrins in the liver and skin. When these porphyrins are exposed to light, they generate reactive oxygen species, causing photosensitivity and the characteristic skin manifestations. PCT can be hereditary or acquired, with the acquired form being more common and often triggered by environmental factors that increase oxidative stress or iron overload.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older individuals (60-80 years) and is characterized by large, tense blisters often accompanied by severe pruritus. It does not explain this patient\u0027s hypertrichosis, hyperpigmentation, or dark urine. Additionally, bullous pemphigoid lesions are less likely to rupture easily as they are subepidermal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermolysis bullosa\u003C/strong\u003E is usually an inherited condition presenting from birth or early childhood. While it can cause blistering on trauma-prone areas, it doesn\u0027t explain the hyperpigmentation, hypertrichosis, or dark urine seen in this patient. Moreover, epidermolysis bullosa doesn\u0027t typically show a predilection for sun-exposed areas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by skin thickening and fibrosis, often affecting the fingers (sclerodactyly) and face. This patient shows no signs of skin thickening or other systemic features typically associated with scleroderma, such as Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon or internal organ involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute presentation often occurring in patients with an existing diagnosis of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE). While it can affect sun-exposed areas, it often involves the face and may affect mucosal surfaces, which are not involved in this case. Bullous lupus also doesn\u0027t account for the hypertrichosis or dark urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has several risk factors that increase her susceptibility to PCT, including a history of hepatitis, blood transfusions, smoking, alcohol use, and long-term oestrogen use (oral contraceptive). These factors can reduce the activity of uroporphyrinogen decarboxylase (UROD), the enzyme deficient in PCT, by increasing oxidative stress and iron retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of blistering on sun-exposed skin, easy bruising, hyperpigmentation, hypertrichosis, dark urine, and multiple risk factors strongly supports the diagnosis of porphyria cutanea tarda.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Always consider porphyria cutanea tarda (PCT) in a patient presenting with a blistering rash on sun-exposed skin.","Porphyria cutanea tarda is associated with risk factors such as hepatitis, alcohol use, smoking, and oestrogen therapy.","Characteristic features of PCT include blistering after minor trauma, hypertrichosis, and dark urine."],"references":["Andersen J, Gjengedal E, Sandberg S, R\u00e5heim M. A skin disease, a blood disease or something in between? An exploratory focus group study of patients\u0027 experiences with porphyria cutanea tarda. Br J Dermatol. 2015 Jan;172(1):223-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24958197/","Welsh B. Blistering skin conditions. Aust Fam Physician. 2009 Jul;38(7):484-90. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/3cb6d77d-88b9-4e8e-bf20-76abf3982e10/Blistering-skin-conditions.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40204"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"662"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18200"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18200"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29230582-293d-4ad1-8366-9d6d89e9ca87.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29230582-293d-4ad1-8366-9d6d89e9ca87.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":361}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40204"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T10:42:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T10:44:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"662"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54677"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i